		<td valign=top width=452><table cellspacing="4" cellpadding="6" width=100% border=0><tr><td background="/images/newsback.gif"><CENTER><H3><FONT FACE="ARIAL" color="#CB723D">Krimson Sun</FONT></H3></CENTER>
			
		<b>Level:</b> Pick One<br>

		<b>Race:</b> Human<br>

		<b>Class:</b> Shadow Knight<br>

		<b>PvP Switch:</b>  On<br>
		
		<center><h4>History:</h4></center>  	“Care for a drink?” a voice behind me asked.<p>	I turned to see the beaming face of an overweight merchant sitting next to me.  I guessed that his generosity was due to the fact that he had just made a big sale.  “Of course,” I replied.<p>	He motioned for the bartender to pour another mug of ale.  “So,” he said as we waited for the drink to arrive, “tell me a little about yourself.  I can see that you are an adventurer of some sort, you must have some fine tales.  Tell me a few.”<p>	I mumbled a thank you as the bartender passed me my mug.  I took a quick drink and stared intensely at the merchant.  “Let me begin by saying there are many types of killers in this world.  There are those who kill for their country, those who kill for their god, those who kill for their guild and those who kill for a cause.  There are also those who kill to saved loved ones and so on.  Then there are a select few who kill for the love of killing.  Nothing gives these few more joy than watching a seasoned soldier beg for his life, tears flooding from his eyes.  Yes, the kill is more exciting to these people than lying in bed next to the high elf princess of Faydwer.  I am one of them.<p>	“My story begins when I was fifteen.  At least I think I was fifteen.  In truth, I have no clue how old I was, or am for that matter.  My first vivid memory is that of a paladin leaning forward, hand extended.  Evidently, I was the prisoner of some dark mage who stole young children from their parents to perform his twisted experiments.  All I remember before the paladin is talking to spirits and wraiths.  I do not recall what they told to me, but I do remember speaking to them.<p>“In any event, the paladins of Karana caught wind of this mage and assaulted his laboratory.  Several of their number died in the attack, but they managed to kill the mage.  They also freed all of his captives.  Of the hundred or so prisoners, roughly half were driven mad by the experiments.  They killed themselves shortly after seeing the sun for the first time in countless years.  The rest of us were brought to the paladins’s stronghold.  There they taught skills that would help us in life: swordplay, theology, reading and writing, and basic mathematics.  The paladins also searched for our parents, and were amazing successful at finding them.  After five years in their stronghold, all but five of us had been returned to their parents.<p>“The paladins were also the ones who gave me my name,” I said while running my hand through my red hair.  “Krimson Sun, because my hair is supposedly as crimson as the morning sun.<p>“After five years of searching, the paladins decided that there was no hope of finding the rest of our parents.  They may have known that our parents were dead and did not tell us or may be they just gave up hope of finding them.  I am leaning toward the former because I have never known a paladin to admit defeat.  The paladins told us that we were free to leave, but offered to teach us the ways of a paladin is we so desired.  All of my comrades decided to join the paladins.  I chose to leave.<p>“The paladins gave me a sword of fine construction, enough provisions to last several weeks and their blessings.  They also told me that their invitation would still stand if I ever wished to return.  I have always kept that invitation in the back of my mind, but now, I doubt that I will ever be able to return.<p>“I wandered Norrath for several years, selling my sword to the highest bidder.  I have fought for the nobles of Qeynos and the pirate lords of Freeport.  I have killed ogres from Oggok when they ventured into the plains of Karana.  I have held back barbarian invasions from Halas.  I was to sole survivor of a poorly planned invasion of Neriak.  (The entire force of five hundred seasoned mercenaries was cut down before we walked a mile into the Nektulos Forest.  I had to kill ten Drow alone to escape to the relative safety of the Kithicok Woods.)  I have served as a bodyguard for one of Erudin’s most powerful sorcerers.  I have taken part in raids on Faydwer to steal the treasures of the elves and dwarves.  I have also been hired by the mages of Erudin to kill the necromancers of Paineel.<p>“It was then that I found my true calling.  There I discovered what I was meant to be.  Most of the necromancers I was able to kill before they knew I was standing behind them.  But the last one saw me before my blade found his heart.  He called forth spirits and wraiths to protect him, but they simply watched as I shortened him a little bit.  Then they talked to me.  Their words were both beautiful and frightening.  For the first time in my life, I knew fear.  But then, I found peace.  I soon discovered that I preferred the company of the undead to that of the living.  That moment marked the beginning of my life as a shadow knight.”<p>I finished my drink and looked at the merchant.  His smile had turned into a look of abject fear and his drunken red cheeks had turned into bone white.  “Do not worry,” I said with a reassuring smile, “I doubt that you made good company as a zombie.”<p>He flashed a weak smile and ordered another drink.<p>I grinned again and watched as the serving wench walked by.  Where the merchant would probably make bad company, she on the other hand…  “So,” I said while turning to face the merchant again, “now that you a little about my character, would you like to hear about my adventures?”  Without waiting for a reply, I asked, “Have you ever seen the pure white buildings of Felwithe?  No?  Let me tell you about the time I was there.  There were over a thousand of us…”<br>
